<div id="review_1367089880" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1367089880" />
    <a title="Pink" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14084605-pink"><img alt="Pink" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1366445251p2/14084605.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1367089880?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pink" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pink" href="/user/show/14084605-pink">Pink</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1367089880" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8549854997465913621">Where to start with this? Okay, if I&apos;m completely honest, although I&apos;ve long considered the justice system in America to have grave institutional racism, I&apos;ve probably always looked at this the wrong way around. Being black in America = having less opportunities and resources. When that comes to living in ghettoised areas, with no jobs, inadequate schooling, bad housing and no foreseeable way out, turning to a life of crime may look like an easy and understandable option. But what if it isn&apos;t th</span>
  <span id="freeText8549854997465913621" style="display:none">Where to start with this? Okay, if I'm completely honest, although I've long considered the justice system in America to have grave institutional racism, I've probably always looked at this the wrong way around. Being black in America = having less opportunities and resources. When that comes to living in ghettoised areas, with no jobs, inadequate schooling, bad housing and no foreseeable way out, turning to a life of crime may look like an easy and understandable option. But what if it isn't the lack of a home, money or opportunities that drives people to break the law, but being unfairly targeted within the system, having done nothing, or little wrong, that leads to being labelled as a criminal. So now you cannot get a job, home, or financial assistance, as you are no longer a worthwhile member of the community, deserving of help. Now what do you do to keep a roof over your head? Who can you turn to when you'll be arrested just for hanging out in your home area, with your previous associates, or as they are often otherwise known, friends and family? How can you make money, yet stay out of trouble, when government agencies seem to be trying their hardest to make things difficult. If it was hard enough before being labelled a criminal, think how hard it is after.<br /><br />Now I'm not saying that all offenders, black or white, are innocent victims. Of course there's a lot of bad motherfuckers out there, who we'd happily keep off the streets, no matter what your views are on incarceration. But what about non-violent crimes? Yes personal drug use, but also small misdemeanours like breaking traffic laws, which every single car driver has done in their life. Only some of us get purposely targeted with an agenda. Not everyone who breaks the law needs a jail sentence, but what colour your skin is makes a difference, in whether you'll be let off, or offered a plea bargain. Threats of a felony record and losing your children, make a guilty plea look like the wiser option, but without having a lifetime of consequences explained to you. Rarely does anyone actually go to court. <br /><br />As for the war on drugs. This isn't about targeting the organised crime gangs making $$$ and causing a menace to society. If it was, they'd be the ones getting prosecuted. Instead, it's about going after certain groups of small time drug users. Marijuana, a drug that's largely been decriminalised, enabling plenty of clean cut white men to profit, is not an option to those with criminal records. So what could have been an avenue into legal employment is still a closed door to many black, previously convicted users. In states where it's still a crime, the white teenager is rarely targeted, or if they are caught, they're seen as blowing of steam and often given a second chance, an opportunity rarely afforded to black teenagers. Of the harder drugs, we have the mostly white used cocaine, with it's much lessor sentencing of the black used crack. It doesn't take a genius to realise why some drugs are targeted above others and it's not about their harmful effects, it's about who uses them. Now I'm not disillusioned enough to think that all drug users are nice people. Some are violent offenders, but that's a separate crime to be dealt with, some are neglecting their children and while that's of vital importance to address, a prison sentence and criminal record is unlikely to make anyone's situation better. <br /><br />I should point out that in the short space of this review, I can only put forward a very simplistic opinion. The issue of drug use and criminality is a lot more complex than I can possibly tackle here. Complete decriminalisation is an option, but it's not where things currently stand. So without giving all black male drug users a free pass, we should still examine why they have disproportionally higher conviction rates and longer sentences than white males. Is this an unbelievable coincidence that happens year on year, or part of a larger agenda? <br /><br />I feel like I'm waffling, but it's hard to review a book that I have so much to say about. Yet, I hardly know where to begin. The topic of mass incarceration is so immense, with no apparent end in sight and trying to comprehend a solution makes my brain hurt. It saddens me to think the only foreseeable changes in the system will just make the situation worse. Politicians and media continue to spout about the 'war on drugs' if only when they take a breath from the 'war on terror' that apparently occupies the world right now. <br /><br />So, I guess if you've read this book, you probably picked it up because, like me, you recognised that something's wrong with the system, but you wanted to learn more. In some ways this isn't telling us anything we don't already know, but it's backing up our concerns with facts and statistics that really bring home how bad things are. <br /><br />If you're not the sort of person who wants to read this book, because you think the criminal justice system does it's job by keeping offenders off the street, with no racial targeting, then I guess this book is for you too. Though perhaps you won't even read the first page. <br /><br />It serves well to remember why this book is entitled The New Jim Crow and just how accurate that is. Racism is still prevalent everywhere in the world and the fascist far right movements currently sweeping Europe are just another reminder of how far we still have to progress. Yet there really seems to be no place quite like America when it comes to disparity between races. It's history is quite unique and far too recent to have moved much further forward in it's evolution of racism. In 400 years it's progressed from genocide, to slavery, to the Jim Crow era of segregation, to the mass incarceration of today. It really is that simple a line of progression. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8549854997465913621" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


